XRD information of the CQDs/BiOCl photocatalysts was manifested in Fig. 1
                        . The diffraction peaks dovetail with the tetragonal phase BiOCl (JCPDS No. 06–0249) [5]. With the addition of CQDs, the diffraction peak strength of the (001) plane of BiOCl gradually weakens, suggesting that CQDs can restraint the growth of the (001) crystal plane. And each individual XRD information of the samples was shown in Fig. S1. Although the growth of (001) crystal plane of the sample is inhibited, the crystallinity of the catalyst has not been obviously affected (Table 1
                        ). In view of the Bragg equation, the interplanar crystal spacing of the (001) plane of CQDs/BiOCl shortens and lattice arrangement becomes sparse, which is favorable to the generation of oxygen vacancies (OVs). The results strongly prove that an intense influence arises between CQDs and BiOCl. The strong interaction is propitious to prevent the agglomeration of the carriers and enhance the catalytic performance of CQDs/BiOCl. Furthermore, thanks to good dispersion and low content of CQDs, no obvious CQDs diffraction peaks were observed. Nevertheless, the presence of CQDs can be further corroborated by HRTEM measurements.
